# Game/Replay/DragAnimation.elm — EARLY

The drag-animation sub-state-machine. Pure physics; the
outer replay orchestrator (`Game.Replay.Time`) calls
`step` on every animation frame and reacts to the
returned `Step`.

## Status

- **Label:** EARLY. Extracted 2026-04-28 from the
  inlined `Animating` branch in `Game.Replay.Time.update`,
  per Steve's "drag animation should be its own little
  state machine" framing.
- **Why factored out:** drag animation is deterministic
  (time + path + source → cursor; cursor at end → done),
  which makes it lockable-down with rigorous property
  tests. The broader replay state machine carries
  volatile UX-tuning values (PreRolling holds, beat
  durations, AwaitingHandRect) that don't want strict
  tests. The seam between this module and `Time` is the
  **testability boundary**.

## Exports

- `Step` — the result of advancing one frame:
  - `InProgress { drag : DragState }` — animation still
    running; outer should render `drag`.
  - `Done { pendingAction : WireAction }` — animation
    complete; outer should apply `pendingAction` and
    advance to the next phase.
- `step : Float -> Space.AnimationInfo -> Step` — pure
  function of clock time + animation info.

## Pointers

- `Game/Replay/Space.elm` — owns `AnimationInfo`,
  `pathDuration`, `interpPath`, `animatedDragState`. This
  module orchestrates those primitives.
- `Game/Replay/Time.elm` — the outer replay state
  machine that calls `step` from its `Animating` branch.
- `tests/Game/Replay/DragAnimationTest.elm` — property
  + boundary tests for `step`.
